As in the Sahel nations, Guatemala and Kyrgyzstan, attempts to introduce abortion procedures enforced by human rights-based activism brought about extreme positions by lawmakers and RNAs. By controllating access strictly, they advocated roles that best suits their personal convictions but create significant barriers. To complicate reproductive health for women even further, constraints are positioned on services to relieve circumstances like rape, incest, trauma and health risk [48]. Similar conditions of coercion for women are featured in Kyrgyzstan, Uganda, Jordan, Guatemala and Brazil. These restrictions may now be appreciated more expertly since reproductive health laws in neighbouring Mali and Niger fail to include a point-for-point fight those put in place by the government of Gabon, thereby depriving many women access to reproductive health solutions [48,50]. There are exceptions in Liberia, where women can use abortion service up to 8 weeks of pregnancy, yet only for specified moral grounds, and in Cameroon, where women can obtain an abortion at any stage if a specific authorized narrow list of moral conditions are enjoyed [46,46].
A key state function is the prevention of violence against women. Prominent behaviors include control of marital forcing and sexual violence, among other offences.
